## Task 3 – Types of Linux Shells

Identifying Shells
echo $SHELL: shows current shell.
- cat /etc/shells: lists all installed shells.
Switch shells by typing their name (e.g., zsh).
Permanently change default shell: chsh -s /usr/bin/zsh.
Common Shells
Bourne Again Shell (Bash)
- Default in most Linux distros.
Features: scripting, tab completion, command history.
- Friendly Interactive Shell (Fish)
Focuses on user-friendliness.
- Features: simple syntax, auto spell correction, customizable prompts/themes, syntax highlighting.
Z Shell (Zsh)
- Modern shell combining features of previous shells.
- Features: advanced tab completion, auto spell correction, extensive customization (e.g., oh-my-zsh).
Comparison Table
Feature	            |     Bash          |	      Fish          |	           Zsh                  |
Scripting           |	Widely compatible |	Limited	            | combines Bash + extras          |
Tab completion      |	Basic             |	Advanced suggestions|	Highly extensible via plugins   |
Customization       |	Basic             |	Good customization  |	Advanced frameworks             |
User friendliness   |	Less user-friendly|	Most user-friendly  |	User-friendly with customization|
Syntax highlighting |	Not available	    | Built-in            |	Available via plugins           |     

